    "summary": "The Germanic Migration Period (c. 375–568 AD, also called the Völkerwanderung) was the massive movement of Germanic and other peoples — Goths, Vandals, Burgundians, Franks, Angles, Saxons, Lombards, and others — across the collapsing frontiers of the Western Roman Empire, fundamentally reshaping the ethnic, political, and cultural map of Europe. Triggered in part by Hunnic pressure from the east, which pushed western nomadic and semi-nomadic peoples into Roman territory, the migrations transformed the Roman provinces into the predecessor kingdoms of medieval Europe.\n\nThe migrations unfolded over roughly two centuries in overlapping waves: Visigoths crossed the Danube in 376, eventually sacking Rome in 410 ([[event:2033|Sack of Rome by Visigoths]]); Vandals swept through Gaul, crossed into Spain, then into North Africa; Angles and Saxons crossed the North Sea into Britain; Franks settled northern Gaul and became the dominant western power under Clovis ([[event:2041|Frankish Kingdom under Clovis]]). The process was not simple invasion but complex interaction — mercenary service, treaty settlement, intermarriage with Roman aristocracy, and gradual Christianization were all part of how Germanic peoples became Romans while also dismantling Roman political structures. The resulting patchwork of Germanic kingdoms formed the foundations of medieval France, Germany, Spain, England, and Italy.",
